Environmental and chemical exposures and reactions
My voice makes it difficult for people to hear me
People have difficulty understanding me in a noisy room
My voice difficulties restrict personal and social life
I feel left out of conversations because of my voice
My voice problem cause me to lose income
I feel as though I have to strain to produce voice
The clarity of my voice is unpredictable
My voice makes me feel handicapped
People ask, “What’s wrong with your voice?”
Gradual, preceded by recurrent and prolonged laryngitis
Frequent voice loss, roughness, and strain in the voice
Sudden, subacute, generally worse acutely with mild improvement over time
Significant roughness and strain. Difficulty with projection and very inconsistent voice
Sudden onset of voice loss with improvement almost back to baseline
In the beginning, severe roughness and strain
Preceding history of intubation or gradual onset
Globus sensation, excessive throat clearing, roughness, and vocal strain
Preceding history of surgery or laryngeal trauma, gradual loss of voice
Gradual loss of voice and projection. One of the rare physiological causes of aphonia
Progressive difficulty primarily with projecting the voice and stamina
Voice is strained and rough, but often not weak. Breathing symptoms predominate
Breathy, weak, and asthenic voice. Easy vocal fatigue and pitch may increase. May complain of breathlessness
Voice is typically rough and strained with decreased pitch

figures.alternate_text: Cross-sectional anatomical diagram of tissue layers. The image shows labeled layers including the epithelium, superficial layer, intermediate layer, deep layer, and muscle. The lamina propria is indicated as encompassing the superficial, intermediate, and deep layers. The diagram highlights the structural organization of these layers.

Endoscopic images showing the vocal cords. The left image displays the vocal cords in an open position, while the right image shows them in a closed position. The surrounding tissue appears pink and vascular.

Endoscopic image of vocal cords, showing a close-up view of the larynx. The vocal cords appear slightly open, with visible tissue and blood vessels. The image is taken from an internal perspective, highlighting the anatomical structure and texture of the area.

Close-up endoscopic image of human vocal cords, showing the glottis in an open position. The surrounding tissue appears pink and vascular, with visible blood vessels. The image is focused on the anatomical structure of the larynx.

Endoscopic image showing the interior of a human throat, highlighting the vocal cords. The image captures the pinkish tissue and the opening of the airway, with the vocal cords visible in the center. The lighting emphasizes the texture and color variations of the surrounding tissue.

Endoscopic image showing the vocal cords. The cords appear pink with some white areas, surrounded by the reddish tissue of the larynx. The image is taken from inside the throat, focusing on the structure and condition of the vocal cords.

Endoscopic image of the larynx showing medical conditions. Labels indicate 'Granulation tissue' on the left, 'Subglottic stenosis' with an arrow pointing to a narrowed area, 'Arytenoid erosion' on the right, and 'Vocal fold paralysis' at the bottom. The image highlights the anatomical structures and pathological changes within the throat.
